shared_text:
Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
Yesterday at 3:38 PM Â·

â€œTime is passing. Yet, for the United States of America, there will be no forgetting September the 11th. We will remember every rescuer who died in honor. We will remember every family that lives in grief. We will remember the fire and ash, the last phone calls, the funerals of the children.â€

19 years have passed since the tragedies of 9/11, and many of us still remember it like it was yesterday. We remember sorrow, pain, and fear. We also remember unity, love, sacrifice, and resilience. We remember the incredibly brave firefighters, police officers, EMS personnel, and other first responders who gave their lives. And we remember the many other lives lost. Let us always remember and honor the lives lost, and the lessons learned in unity and sacrifice. Let us never forget 9/11.

shared_text:
Jessamine County Health Department
August 31 at 10:26 AM Â·

Here in Jessamine County, we have lost too many parents, siblings, friends, and loved ones to overdose death.

But an overdose doesnâ€™t have to be the end. It could be the beginning of hope for someone. If someone you know is at risk of narcotic overdose, consider carrying Narcan. You might just save a life.

Narcan is available to anyone in the community, no questions asked. You can come see us at the Jessamine County Health Department for training and a free Narcan kit whenever our doors are open.

August 11 at 9:03 AM Â·

***REMINDER***
The Jessamine County Sheriff's Office has seen a rise in vehicle break-ins and trailer thefts in the past several weeks. Just a reminder, lock all valuables up inside and outside of your home. Please document all serial numbers of value and store in a safe place. If you observe any suspicious behavior, please call Jessamine County E911. Non-emergency- 859-887-5447.

COVID-19 can be spread by people who do not have symptoms and do not know that they are infected. Masks can help prevent people who have COVID-19 from spreading the virus to others. shared_text:
Jessamine County (KY) Emergency Management Agency / C-S-E-P-P
June 1 at 2:32 PM Â·

After days of searching, crews were able to recover the body of the missing man from Lock 7 in High Bridge. Many family members were on scene today as crews from Jessamine County and Lexington removed the man from the Kentucky River in Jesaamine County after 5 days of searching. This incident brings to life the reality of how dangerous and how quickly things can change with swift water conditions on any body of water. We are grateful for the outpouring of support and manpower from Jessamine County Fire District, Nicholasville Fire Department, Wilmore Fire Department, Kentucky Fish and Wildlife Law Enforcement, Jessamine County Sheriff 's Office, Jessamine County EMS, Jessamine County Coroner's office, Lexington Fire Department, Anderson County Fire District, Woodford County Fire District and Woodford County Emergency Management, Commonwealth and Grand Paws Search Dog Teams and Keeneland Chaplain services and Kentucky Emergency Management.
Please be safe around Rivers Lakes and Streams and always use a personal flotation device.
We express our condolences to the family.

Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
May 28 at 3:09 PM Â·

You may have noticed several new faces around Jessamine County EMS lately! We would like to introduce you to two of our newest employees: EMT Jared Adams and EMT Madison Phillips.

Both EMT Adams and EMT Phillips have successfully completed their field training orientation and have been released to work without the supervision of a preceptor. We canâ€™t wait to watch these two continue to grow here at JCEMS and see the impact that they will have on this community. Please welcome EMT Adams and EMT Phillips to Jessamine County and be on the lookout for some more of our newest hires as they complete their field training orientations!

shared_text:
Jessamine County Fire District
May 24 at 8:41 PM Â·

The Jessamine County Fire District and the Nicholasville Fire Department have had a busy day. First both departments responded to a cow that was stuck in a creek and our Large Animal Rescue Technicians were able to remove the cow and she is now recovering. Then our departments responded to a fire at a local factory where all occupants were able to safely evacuate and property damage was kept to a minimum. Our departments always come together and provide the best service for the citizens of Jessamine County and Nicholasville.

Thank you! #TogetherJessamine #TeamJessamine

Central Kentucky Hauling will be closed Monday, May 25 th , 2020 so that we may honor those who served and enjoy time at home with our families.

Jessamine County and the city of Nicholasville residential trash and recycling collections will be pushed back one day from your normal schedule (Monday routes will run Tuesday, Tuesday routes will run Wednesday, Wednesday routes will run Thursday, Thursday routes will run Friday and Friday routes will run Saturday).

We wish our customers in Jessamine County and the city of Nicholasville a safe and happy Memorial Day!

shared_text:
Jessamine Fair
May 13 at 9:15 AM Â·

It is with great sadness that the Jessamine County Fair Board has made the decision to cancel the fair this year, we feel the health and safety of our community is more important. This decision was made after consulting with local leaders and carefully reviewing the steps in reopening of the Commonwealth of Kentucky.
We will continue preparing for year 2021. The Jessamine County Fair Board will be working on building new restrooms that will be handicap accessible and remodeling our current bathrooms with grant money we received this year.
The month of July we would like to invite you to help keep the spirit of the Jessamine County Fair alive by posting memories along with pictures.

Jessamine County Health Department updated their cover photo.
April 20 at 10:45 AM Â·

The Health Department has limited testing capacity and will screen individuals for specific eligibility criteria. Those with symptoms associated with COVID-19 (fever, cough, shortness of breath, and diarrhea) will receive priority for testing. Other asymptomatic high risk populations including healthcare workers, first responders and individuals that live or work in congregate care settings may also qualify for testing.

A verification process will be performed by JCHD staff and only those qualifying will be scheduled for an appointment to receive the no cost testing. Individuals without an appointment will not be seen.

Find out if you are eligible by completing the COVID-19 Screening Tool provided by IBM & IBM Watson located at www.jessaminehealth.org or by calling 859-885-4149.

The drive-thru COVID-19 testing site is an effort by the Jessamine County Health Department, Kentucky Department for Public Health, and Gravity Diagnostics.

post_text:
Notice to All Jessamine County and City of Nicholasville Curbside Recycling Customers:

The LFUCG Recycling Center, where all curbside recycling materials are processed, has closed for the next 4 weeks due to mechanical issues. Effective immediately, all material that residents set out for pickup in their trash and recycling carts will be treated as trash and disposed of at the Lexington Transfer Station. Residents do have the option to store their recyclables themselves for collection and processing once the recycling center opens back up in the estimated 4-week time frame. CKY will post a notice on its website when the Lexington Recycling Center reopens. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause our customers.

âœ…Clean and disinfect surfaces regularly

Don'ts

shared_text:
Jessamine County Food Pantry
March 18 at 8:36 AM Â·

The Pantry now has three options for our neighbors needing food assistance.

1. Pick up a box (think the old style method from several years ago). You get canned and boxed foods, potatoes, rice and beans, and frozen meats. Totals just over 50 lbs of food. A good option for smaller families.

2. Come into the pantry and "shop". We are limiting the number of individuals in the store at any one time so we can maintain social distancing. This may be the best option for larger families.

3. If you are quarantined or over 60 call 859-312-4003. We have several people who have volunteered to make deliveries for the duration of the Covid-19 crisis. Be patient on the phone please; if we don't answer, leave a message and we will return your call as soon as we can.

shared_text:
Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
February 21 at 11:00 AM Â·

You may have noticed some new faces here at JCEMS over the last few days! We would love for you to give a warm welcome to our newest hires, EMT Houston Chamblin, EMT Ciera Denton, EMT Miriam Lancaster, EMT Luis Soler, and EMT Matt Wickham!

This group completed the classroom portion of their orientation last week, and this week they have started on the trucks riding third person with their Field Training Officer. Our classroom portion consists of a lot of lecture in topics like operations, protocols, and treatments, but also gave providers a chance to run scenarios and practice skills. This classroom portion provides a solid foundation of skills for our Field Training Officers to continue developing now as these new employees complete their field training. We are looking forward to watching Houston, Ciera, Miriam, Luis, and Matt continue to grow and are so excited for their future here at JCEMS!
text:
Welcome!

Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
February 21 at 11:00 AM Â·

You may have noticed some new faces here at JCEMS over the last few days! We would love for you to give a warm welcome to our newest hires, EMT Houston Chamblin, EMT Ciera Denton, EMT Miriam Lancaster, EMT Luis Soler, and EMT Matt Wickham!

This group completed the classroom portion of their orientation last week, and this week they have started on the trucks riding third person with their Field Training Officer. Our classroom portion consists of a lot of lecture in topics like operations, protocols, and treatments, but also gave providers a chance to run scenarios and practice skills. This classroom portion provides a solid foundation of skills for our Field Training Officers to continue developing now as these new employees complete their field training. We are looking forward to watching Houston, Ciera, Miriam, Luis, and Matt continue to grow and are so excited for their future here at JCEMS!

shared_text:
Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services is with Kris Ogden and 7 others.
February 4 at 3:16 PM Â·

Our providers experienced a unique and incredible opportunity for learning today. JCEMS EMTs and Paramedics traveled to the University of Louisville School of Medicine for skills practice. We partnered with the Willed Body Program for access to a cadaver, and we were able to work on airway management, video laryngoscopy, needle decompression, and humeral IO access. These are such important skills that are less frequently performed in the field and are often difficult to mimic on a mannequin, making this experience invaluable! We would like to extend a huge thank you to the U of L School of Medicine, and Dr. Nicole Herring of the Willed Body Program for welcoming us this week!

Great work!

post_text:
ATTENTION ALL JESSAMINE COUNTY
CURBSIDE RECYCLING CUSTOMERS

CKY Hauling takes all curbside recycling materials it collects to the Lexington Recycling Center for processing. The Recycling Center will be shut down for improvements (January 6, 2020 through January 19, 2020). CKY Hauling and the Recycling Center do not have the ability to store recyclables while the facility improvements are made. CKY Hauling asks that all recycling customers hold their recycling for collection the week of January 20th. For customers that cannot store their recycling materials CKY will continue to run its residential recycling routes during the shutdown period, but the materials will have to be landfilled. Further information regarding the Lexington Recycling Center shut down can be found at: https://www.lexingtonky.gov/RecycleUpdates

Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
November 5, 2019 at 7:44 AM Â·

Jessamine County EMS crew training days are much different than the average. Friday we spent the day reviewing redacted charts curated by our Clinical Manager and Medical Director. Followed by simulation based education utilizing our grant purchased Hamilton T1 ventilator and simulation equipment. In the picture below, our patient (Chief Goodpaster) is wearing an IV sleeve to make the scenario more realistic and interactive while acting the part of a patient experiencing respiratory distress and later a stable ventricular tachycardia.

Clinical Manager Floyd Miracle works diligently to develop high yield education that builds our team into highly effective medical providers. I hope our community is proud of the work we are doing and feels confident our providers are adequately trained and prepared for your emergency.

Great job at training, team!

Jessamine County E911
October 18, 2019 at 2:30 PM Â·

Jessamine County E911 would like to congratulate Haven McKenney and Amanda Comley, two of our newest dispatchers on not only graduating from DOCJT Public Safety Dispatch Academy Class 128, but both graduated as Trainees of Distinction! Not only were both ladies Trainees if Distinction, their class was a Class of Distinction, something that only FIVE academy classes since the late 90â€™s has achieved. In order for a trainee to be a Trainee of Distinction they must maintain a GPA of 95 or above. For a class to be a Class of Distinction the overall class must maintain a GPA of 96 or above. Haven was also one of four squad leaders for the class, meaning that she was in charge of four other trainees, reminding them when to be where and the rules and regulations they are to follow while in the academy. We are very proud of these ladies and all they have accomplished during their time away and are excited to have them join us back in dispatch!!

shared_text:
Jessamine County (KY) Emergency Management Agency / C-S-E-P-P
September 27, 2019 at 12:31 AM Â·

A lengthy search for a missing hiker has a happy ending tonight. Crews were called to the Jessamine Creek Gorge for a person in distress. An adult female contacted Jessamine County 911 reporting that she had become lost in the gorge area while out jogging on the trails. She had gotten off of the trails and tried to navigate toward a familiar location to find her way out. After an hour of hiking she realized she was lost and called for help. Agencies from Jessamine Co EM, Fire Rescue, EMS as well as Nicholasville and Wilmore Fire departments sent team members to aid in the search which lasted around 4 hours. The person was found successfully because she did as she was asked of her by responders and stayed where she was once her location was pinged by the communicators. Crews had to travel well off of the trail system to finally make contact. She was able to walk out with the crews and was evaluated by Jessamine EMS but did not require transport.
text:
Great job!

Jessamine County (KY) Emergency Management Agency / C-S-E-P-P
September 27, 2019 at 12:31 AM Â·

A lengthy search for a missing hiker has a happy ending tonight. Crews were called to the Jessamine Creek Gorge for a person in distress. An adult female contacted Jessamine County 911 reporting that she had become lost in the gorge area while out jogging on the trails. She had gotten off of the trails and tried to navigate toward a familiar location to find her way out. After an hour of hiking she realized she was lost and called for help. Agencies from Jessamine Co EM, Fire Rescue, EMS as well as Nicholasville and Wilmore Fire departments sent team members to aid in the search which lasted around 4 hours. The person was found successfully because she did as she was asked of her by responders and stayed where she was once her location was pinged by the communicators. Crews had to travel well off of the trail system to finally make contact. She was able to walk out with the crews and was evaluated by Jessamine EMS but did not require transport.

Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
September 15, 2019 at 10:47 AM Â·

We could not be more proud of our team today!

Yesterday members of Jessamine County EMS competed in a simulation challenge at the reinventing prehospital medicine conference. They encountered critical simulated patients in each scenario and brought home the win after successfully managing a complex simulated mass casualty incident. Sgt. Kellie Niswender, Paramedic Karen Vasatka, Paramedic Mohammad Shalash, and last minute team member Paramedic Daniel Skinner (Hopkinsville Fire and EMS) deserve a round of applause for their expert management and teamwork in these scenarios.

Join us in congratulating our team on their win!

Kellie Niswender, Paramedic Karen Vasatka, Paramedic Mohammad Shalash, and last minute team member Paramedic Daniel Skinner (Hopkinsville Fire and EMS) deserve a round of applause for their expert management and teamwork in these scenarios.

Join us in congratulating our team on their win!

It is that time of year again when school starts back and things start getting a little hectic. Please remember starting Wednesday kids will be out in full force waiting and riding on our buses. With that being said the photo here is a friendly reminder of Kentucky law as it pertains to buses in our community. Please pay special attention to our kids out and our buses on the roadway. There is no place that you have to be in such a rush that you jeopardize everyone's safety.

Also, keep in mind that our Safety Officers will be directing traffic at our schools. Please be patient as the first couple of weeks can be a little hectic. Keep them safe by paying attention to their directions and remember to use extra caution in our school zones.

Thanks again and have a good year!!

shared_text:
Nicholasville
July 30, 2019 at 11:44 AM Â·

We are pleased to officially announce that the Kentucky Transportation Cabinet has funded the Nicholasville East High Trail project. The City was notified July 17th that our $700,000 project was included as one of 42 projects in the State. This phase of the project will finalize the right of way and relocate utilities. This phase will be the catalyst to pursue construction dollars for the final phase. The Kentucky Transportation Cabinet is actively constructing a new Eastern Bypass and they have included a muli-use path parallel to the bypass. The East High Trail will connect to the Transportation Cabinet's trail and will ultimately provide a connection from West Place subdivision all the way to downtown Nicholasville! This is truly a great opportunity to improve the quality of life for our residents and to provide a safe manner for those students who wish to walk/bike to school.

Jessamine County Emergency Medical Services
July 10, 2019 at 4:46 PM Â·

This week members of JCEMS, JCFD, NFD, and JCSO reviewed our Critical Incident Medical Response and Evacuation procedures. Jessamine County public safety departments have partnered together to reduce the time it takes for medical aid to be provided during an active shooter incident. Traditionally, medical and rescue providers have been ordered to wait until the incident is clear or at least "warm". This has lead to victims waiting three or more hours to receive aid. We train to put our providers in the "hot zone" while the shooter may still be active. Each crew member was briefed on the specifics of response, equipment utilization, operational integrity and safety, and our response plans for high risk sites.

Nicholasville Police Department
July 1, 2019 at 3:10 PM Â·

As the 4th of July approaches we would like to ask for some consideration when it comes to fireworks in our community. We want everyone to be able to celebrate this great holiday but at the same time ask that you please be considerate of your neighbors. Fireworks are a huge part of the holiday celebration and we understand that on the 4th many will participate. It is our hope that all will have a great time but remember that not everyone has the next day off. The Police Department will not be going out looking for fireworks violations but if we receive complaints we will respond. Please try to keep your celebration to a reasonable level and be considerate of everyone as the night gets later. Thank you
